{{Politics of Fiji}}
The '''Justice and Freedom Party''' (JFP) was a minor [[political party]] in [[Fiji]].  It was formed in 2000 to promote the interests of the [[Indians in Fiji|Indo-Fijian]] community, and unsuccessfully contested the [[Fijian general election, 2001|2001]] and [[Fijian general election, 2006|2006]] elections.  It was dissolved in 2013.

In the [[Fijian general election, 2001|2001 election]] the party gained less than 0.1 percent of the popular vote and won no constituencies.  With some 76 percent of Indo-Fijians voting for the [[Fiji Labour Party]] and 22 percent for the [[National Federation Party]], the JFP was squeezed out.

In the [[Fijian general election, 2006|2006 elections]], the party intended to run candidates in all 19 [[communal constituencies]] allocated to Indo-Fijians, and on 3 April published a [[manifesto]] promising to petition the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and the [[United Nations]] to press the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Australia]] to accept responsibility for bringing [[India]]ns to Fiji during the [[British Empire|colonial]] era.  It also promised a [[Fijian dollar|F$10 million]] scholarship for Indo-Fijian students.  The party would also push for [[dual citizenship]] to be allowed for Indo-Fijians living in Australia and the United Kingdom, and for British passports to be restored to Indo-Fijians living in Fiji, JFP General Secretary [[Dildar Shah]] said.  On 7 April, however, it was announced that the JFP had decided to merge with the multiracial [[National Alliance Party of Fiji]] under the leadership of [[Ratu]] [[Epeli Ganilau]].  Some JFP members, including Shah, would contest the forthcoming election on 6–13 May for the Alliance, Ganilau said.  However, it did subsequently contest the election, gaining only 18 votes.

In 2006 the Fijian government was overthrown and the Fijian parliament dissolved in a [[2006 Fijian coup d'état|coup]].  In January 2013 the military regime promulgated new regulations governing the registration of political parties, requiring all parties to have at least 5,000 members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/world/south-pacific/8184406/Fiji-regime-cracks-down-on-political-parties |title=Fiji regime cracks down on political parties |publisher=Stuff |author=Michael Field |date=2013-01-16 |accessdate=2013-01-28}}</ref>  The JFP welcomed the new regulations<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=223662 |title=Political party welcomes decree |publisher=Fiji Times |author=Nanise Loanakadavu |date=2013-01-28 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> but was unable to gain the required number of members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbc.com.fj/fiji/8107/justice-and-freedom-party-fails-to-meet-deadline |title=Justice and Freedom Party fails to meet deadline |publisher=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation |date=2013-02-15 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref>  it was therefore wound up and its assets forfeited to the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=225235 |title=Forfeiture |publisher=Fiji Times |author=Tevita Vuibau |date=2013-02-15 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref>

