{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}
'''Mandela and Tambo''' was a South African law firm established by [[Nelson Mandela]] and [[Oliver Tambo]] in Johannesburg in late 1952.  It was the first "Attorney Firm" in the country to be run by black partners.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tambo Moot Court |publisher=University of Cape Town |access-date=9 December 2013 |url=http://www.law.uct.ac.za/about/tambo_moot_court/name/ |date=24 September 2006 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023211220/http://www.law.uct.ac.za/about/tambo_moot_court/name/ |archivedate=23 October 2010 |df= }}</ref>

In August 1952, Mandela had opened his own firm<ref name="Mandela1">{{cite book|title=Long Walk to Freedom:  Vol. 1|last=Mandela|first=Nelson|publisher=Abacus|date=1994|isbn=0349116024}}</ref>{{rp|210}} but, after just several months, he invited Tambo to join him in the establishment of Mandela and Tambo in two small rooms at [[Chancellor House (building)|Chancellor House]], the building housing the headquarters of the African National Congress.  The firm was inundated with clients seeking redress from acts of the oppressive apartheid regime. In South Africa, "Attorney Firms" would deal with lay clients directly and draft most of the paperwork, and "instruct" an Advocate, either practising independently or in-house with the firm, to plead before the Court. Tambo would do much of the paperwork in the office whilst Mandela did most of the advocacy before the magistrates in the courts opposite.<ref name="Mandela1" />{{rp|212}}

Later others joined the firm, including [[Duma Nokwe]], [[Ruth Mompati]], [[Mendi Msimang]] and Godfrey Pitje.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/south-africa-fast-facts/history-facts/chancellor-house-300910|title=New life for Mandela & Tambo Attorneys|website=Brand South Africa|date=1 October 2010|access-date=20 May 2017}}</ref>

The firm was closed down in 1960 as Mandela faced charges of treason and Tambo fled the country.  The building was later gutted by fire and was an urban slum for many years<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 March 2010|last=Smith|first=David|title=Site of Nelson Mandela's historic law office faces redevelopment|access-date=20 May 2017|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/mar/14/nelson-mandela-office-redevelopment-fears}}</ref> before being completely refurbished and opened as a museum and archive in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|date=4 May 2011|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/04/mandela-tambo-law-offices-museum|title=Nelson Mandela's law office reborn as museum |access-date=20 May 2017}}</ref>

